MALARIA - INDONESIA (JAVA)
***************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
[1]
Date: 2 Aug 2000
From: Nicholas Riesland M.D, <rieslandnj@state.gov> [edited]

_P.falciparum_ malaria in Java, Indonesia
-------------------------------------------
Three weeks ago our clinic treated an expatriate for falciparum malaria
contracted in a popular beach-resort area frequented by tourists two hours
west of Jakarta. The main towns in this area are Sambolo and Carita. Prior
to this case, malaria has not been reported frequently enough in this
resort area over the last few years to warrant, in our opinion, a
recommendation for medical prophylaxis, though we have recommended it for
those traveling to the West Javanese national park area of Ujungkulon to
the south of Sambolo-Carita.
Additionally, during the past 4 years there has been a significant increase
in malaria in Central Java Province adjacent to Yogjakarta Province. There
is documented a more than ten-fold increase in some areas like Cilacap and
Purworejo. The reasons for the increase are likely multifactorial. Some
entomologists point out that in recent years control programs (spraying)
have fallen by the wayside due to lack of funding. A recent in vivo drug
resistance study in Purworejo, Central Java found a 35% prevalence of
malaria in the local population with a high level of resistance to
chloroquine by both _P. falciparum_ and _P. vivax_.
Other areas with endemic malaria include Kokop and Parangtritis (beach
area) in Yogyakarta Province and Cilacap and Banjarnegara in Central Java.
_P.falciparum_ accounts for 50-60% of cases in Central Java and 20-30% of
cases in Yogyakarta Province.
Data from the Ministry of Health on Yogyakarta Province suggest an annual
peak incidence of 8 000 slide confirmed cases during 1994. Since then the
number of slide confirmed cases in Yogyakarta Province has been stable at
approximately 2 000 cases per year. Autochthonous malaria within the city
of Yogyakarta has not been confirmed.
Based on this information, antimalarial prophylaxis with either doxycycline
or mefloquine and personal protective measures would be prudent for all
overnight travelers to Central Java and rural Yogyakarta Province, which
lies adjacent to the areas of documented increase, with the exception of
the cities of Semerang and Yogyakarta. All travelers anticipating overnight
stays in rural areas outside these 2 main cities, including Borobudur,
should consider malaria prophylaxis. Post-exposure prophylaxis with
primaquine should also be considered for G6PD normal individuals. We do not
recommend such measures in the major urban areas of Java at this time
including Jakarta, Bogor, Bandung, Solo, and Surabaya.
--
Nicholas Riesland M.D
Regional Medical Officer
U.S. Embassy Jakarta
Tel. 6221-344-2200, ext 2211
