Background information on malaria in Indonesia
------------------------------------------------
_Plasmodium falciparum_ accounts for approximately 66% of cases. _P. ovale_
and _P. malariae_ are common in the Eastern region. Chloroquine-resistant
P. falciparum IS reported. Chloroquine-resistant _P. vivax_ has been
reported since 1991 in Irian Jaya, North Sulawesi, Flores and West
Kalimantan, with highest rates (14%) on Nias.
Malaria accounted for 6.7% of all deaths in this country during 1986.
Risk occurs in all seasons and throughout the country, except in the large
cities. Sumatra and Kalimantan are considered hypoendemic, with the
exception of Nias Island (mesoendemic). Highest rates for Kalimantan are
registered in the eastern portion. Irian Jaya has the highest rates for
eastern Indonesia. Flores Island is classified as meso- to hyperendemic;
Lombok and Sulawesi (north, central and southern portions) as hypo- to
mesoendemic.
33 000 cases were reported in 1988 from Java and Bali, and 22 802 in 1989;
1.64 million in 1990 (including 64 854 in East Timor and 26 018 from Java &
Bali); 1.91 million in 1991 (including 15 506 from Java and Bali); 1.31
million in 1992 (including 13 655 from Java and Bali); 21 847 from Java
(notably Central Province) and Bali (10/100,000) in 1993; 575 000 in 1994
(including 19726 in Java and Bali); 1 460 569 in 1995.
The principal vectors are _Anopheles letifer_, _An. nigerrimus_, _An.
aconitus_, _An. barbirostris_, _An. balabacencis_, _An. dirus_, _An.
leucosphyrus_, _An. ludlowae_, _An. maculatus_, _An. minimus_, _An.
flavirostris_, _An. philippinensis_, _An. sundaicus_. An. sinensis_, _An.
koliensis_ and _An. punctulatus_ (in Irian Jaya).
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The spread of malaria in Java can easily be explained by decreased control
activities as suggested. Sporadic chloroquine resistance has been know in
Indonesia for some years, and the standard prophylactic recommendation for
Europeans is chloroquine and proguanil.
It would be appropriate to have a comment from the authorities on the
report and the suggestion that malaria control activities has been reduced
in recent years, and further data on resistance is important to decide on
relevant prophylaxis. -Mod.EP]
